<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT=""> 

<a name="week1"><b>1.  The Old Testament </b>
</big><br>
<p>

Reading, everyone:
<ul>
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#craft">S&amp;M</a>, Chapters 2 and 3
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#orange">The Orange Book</a>.
Read the preface, intro, Sec 5, Sec 6, Sec 8, Sec 10,
the Appendices, and Glossary are all worth reading.
Skim the rest.  
<li> Read <a href="../resources/index.shtml#saltzer">Saltzer and Schroeder,</a> 
Section 1.  (1A is more important than 1B)
<li> Read <a href="../resources/index.shtml#schell">Schell.</a> 
</ul>
<p>
Additional reading, grad credit:
<ul>
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#mclean">Mclean.</a> (a critique of the lattice approach.)
<li> In <a href="../resources/index.shtml#karger">Karger et al.</a>,
read
 Sections I-III. V, VI, IX and onward are good.
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#bell">Bell and LaPadula.</a> (the
seminal lattice model for secrecy).
</ul>
<P>

Lecture notes:
<ul>
<li> <a href="apr02/index.shtml"><b>Mon, April 2: Information Flow.</b></a>
<li> <a href="apr04/index.shtml"><b>Wed, April 4: The Orange Book.</b></a>
<li> <a href="apr05/index.shtml"><b>Thu, April 5 (X-hour): Old Principles, New World.</b></a>
</ul>
<p><hr><p>

<p>

<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT=""> 

<a name="week2"><b>2. The Cryptographic Toolkit</b>
</big><br>
<p>
Reading:
<ul>
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#craft">S&amp;M</a>, Chapters 7, 10
</ul>
<p>
Graduate reading:
<ul>
<li> R. Kohlas and U. Mauerer.
<a href="http://www.springerlink.com/index/HMLL31Q2J5542C73.pdf"><b>"Reasoning About Public-Key Certification: On Bindings Between Entities and Public Keys."</b></a>.  IEEE Journal on Selected Areas in Communications, 2000.
(You can find more, including the one in which he fumes about PGP,
<a href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~sws/private/maurer/"><b>here</b></a>.)
<li> J. Marchesini, S.W. Smith. 
<a href="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/~sws/pubs/ms05a.pdf"><b>"Modeling Public Key Infrastructure in the Real World."</b></a> Public Key Infrastructure: EuroPKI 2005.  (our follow-up)
<li> 
S. Garfinkel and R. Miller.
<a href="http://cups.cs.cmu.edu/soups/2005/2005proceedings/p13-garfinkel.pdf"><b>"Johnny 2: A User Test of Key Continuity Management with S/MIME and Outlook Express"</b></a>. Symposium on Usable Privacy and Security.
2005.
</ul>
<p>
Lecture notes:
<ul>
<li> <a href="apr06/index.shtml"><b>Fri, April 6: Symmetric Cryptography.</b></a>
<li> <a href="apr09/index.shtml"><b>Mon, April 9: Public Key Cryptography.</b></a>
<li> <a href="apr11/index.shtml"><b>Wed, April 11: In Practice.</b></a>
<li> <a href="apr12/index.shtml"><b>Thu, April 12 (X-hour): PKI.</b></a>
</ul>
<p><hr><p>

<p>

<big><IMG ALIGN="bottom" SRC="http://www.cs.dartmouth.edu/images/greenball.gif" ALT=""> 

<a name="week3"><b>3. Breaking Cryptography</b>
</big><br>
<p>
Reading:
<ul>
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#craft">S&amp;M</a>, Chapter 8.
<li> <a href="http://cryptome.org/cracking-des/cracking-des.htm"><b>Cracking DES</b></a>, Chapters 1 and 2.
<li> The   <a href="../resources/index.shtml#kv4"><b>Dole</b></a> and 
<a href="../resources/index.shtml#gowa">Goldberg/Wagner</b></a> papers 
<li> <a href="../resources/index.shtml#timing">Kocher's timing paper</a>
<li> Graduates might be interested in 
<a href="../resources/index.shtml#hastad"><b>Hastad's
"On Using RSA with Low-Exponent in a Public Key Network"</b></a>
<li> as well as in <a href="../resources/index/shtml#boneh1998"><b>the
Boneh/Venktasen paper</b></a>
</ul>
<p>

Lecture notes:
<ul>
<li> <a href="apr13/index.shtml"><b>Fri, April 13: Subverting Cryptography (Part 1).</b></a>
<li> Mon, April 16: <i>No class: Sean at NSF</i>
<li> Wed, April 18:  <i>No class: Sean at NIST</i>
<li> Thu, April 19 (X-hour): <i>No class: Sean at NIST</i>
<li> <a href="apr20/index.shtml"><b>Fri, April 20: Subverting Cryptography (Part 2).</b></a>
</ul>
